I don't know about you, but when I'm having a stressful conversation, particularly about trauma, I feel too anxious & nauseated to eat snacks at that time. The snacking & comfort eating would usually come afterwards when I'm on the come down.

In the short term stress usually suppresses appetite. The nervous system sends messages to the adrenal glands atop the kidneys to pump out the hormone epinephrine (also known as adrenaline). Epinephrine helps trigger the body's fight-or-flight response, a revved-up physiological state that temporarily puts eating on hold. Reliving trauma in a crowded room would usually create acute short term stress. Maybe she is different, but it is unusual behaviour, especially in the casual way she is doing it.

That said yes it's true, eating could be helping with stress & be a distraction, the stress of having to lie & evade in court & on tape.

@Psychometrix Umm... yeah, that's not how it works... at least not in the US. 

Keeping up with research and continuing education is *required* of pretty much everyone who holds some sort of license in healthcare. My Nursing Assistant/Home Health Aide license alone (which only required 175 hours of class time to get certified)  required 20 credits of continuing education per year. My Pharmacy Tech license requires 40. I literally just submitted the write up for my last couple of 2021 credits
 to my Board of Pharmacy for approval. It was about research on the mechanisms behind tolerance to psychoactive medications and how NMDA antagonists (medications like Ketamine, Namenda, and DXM) prevent it in patients who need to be on certain medications long-term. When SARS-CoV-2 hit, the healthcare system, where I'm doing clinical rotations, required everyone in a DPS position (and all med students on rotations) to complete extra training regarding several areas related to the pandemic. Hell, it was *doctors* who first sounded the alarm over OxyContin. The discovery that Purdue Pharma had falsified their data came when new independent studies couldn't reproduce the results. 

You don't get to graduate and then never look at any material again.

It's a trauma response and a coping mechanism. A lot of us trauma survivors use humor to make our stories bearable for those we tell them to. And also in an attempt to minimize what we've been through - "if I keep acting like it wasn't a big deal, then maybe it will just go away and stop hurting."

When he made the joke about his finger that only solidified to me that the smirk he made was him masking the pain of a bad situation with humor. He does the same thing I do when I remember something bad that's happened. Which is to joke about it to lighten the pain. 

For example, when I landed wrong on a trampoline a few years ago and messed up my knee to the point it popped sideways and I couldn't walk on it for several weeks. I made jokes about it quite often. Hell one of the first thoughts in my mind during the moments following the injury (after the initial pain) was an image of the scene from Ace Ventura with a spear in his knee and the motion he made. Because trying to dampen the pain with humor or seeing the good in the bad is just my natural response.
@Lora-Mae Keogh yes. I've been told I have no emotions and I'm like if you only knew I am a tightly wrapped ball of emotions and if it begins to unravel it's all over.
@Rebecca Caraballo I do this all the time and I don't realise I'm doing it until my friends all look at me with wide eyes and say "that's really dark". It's just my way of coping with my trauma.
I didn't know he did this, but somehow it came across as self soothing, as my brother does this sometimes.

@Jokutällane Vaa Thank you, that last part was exactly my point. It can't be used in court for a reason, and that reason is because it gives the false positives I've been mentioning. Innocent until proven guilty is a great concept unless you're being harassed by the police while being innocent.
We're probably not getting anywhere with this conversation and it seems like I struck a nerve based on your last reply so I'll say bye now.

@Sho Man Listen stop bitching around, if you are acting abnormally, you will be treated like so. Whatever the reason, you can try and say you are autistic and have this and that. And if they are nice, they'll believe you. But I can be on cocaine/alcohol and say the same. Or I just might be a little too sleepy for their liking, and then go through the same. You're not acting normal (=90% of people/no conditions) and most of the ones doing the same ARE problematic, maybe you ain't. But you will be a rarity. Deal with it. Body language works only on people with controll of their body, normal senses/brain functioning, and emotions. If you are part of the people OUTSIDE that ring, it doesn't. And that's why it can't be used as an actual evidence in court for example.

@Jokutällane Vaa No, not after the questioning. After having to put your life on hold and having a stranger watching your private parts while you pee or taking your blood to do tests that always come back negative.

Facts. I have lived and survived or I think I'm surviving through narcissistic abuse

I agree with these replies. This is definitely a way that we (people w ptsd and bpd) cope. To joke about it or laugh about it, even if its just for a second, helps us stay grounded and remember that its not happening now and it won't happen again because its over and dealt with and we now have the privilege to speak about it once happening rather than waiting for it to be over.

As someone with BPD (Borderline Personality Disorder) who disassociates regularly. You couldn’t be more right. He laughs to cope with recalling trauma. He may not even know what trauma he’s recalling it’s the emotions and feelings from it coming up. Our brains pull us away from the situation as a defense. 
When I saw Johnny say he was confused and scared and wanted to go home. I cried. I cried a lot. I felt his pain, that feeling of being trapped. Amber is a liar and she needs to be stopped.
Could it also be shame/embarrassment from the cultural stigma of female on male violence?

@BroPoke679  Yeah, people think that someone laughing or smiling always means they're amused but human psychology is just way more complicated than that or life would be much simpler. A good example is the infamous Logan Paul video from the suicide forest. It's appalling and I can't stand him so it's not really a defense but when he's laughing it's definitely not because he thinks it's funny or doesn't care, it's because he's in shock. I don't think he really anticipated how traumatic it would be to see that and most people would have seemingly antithetical reactions. He's a massive idiot but I don't think he's a sociopath.

Completely sealed the deal for me, even without the commentary.

This isn't even the defiant face of a woman who has fought her way out of a crap relationship, nor does she look like victims I've seen on tv. He does, however. Hell, I do the smirky laugh thing when I'm embarrassed about something and try to make it less bad for myself to talk about.

Psychologically and physically, just like a man can be to a woman. We want to be equal, but sadly it seems to be only for the “right things”. When it’s about violence, crime, abuse (well I’m talking about those who aren’t the real victim but try to act like one) they really love the patriarchal society that we are in. 😪

I can say with some certainty that you are correct. Especially with the perceived power dynamic of her being more assertive and dominant and him being submissive. I have been in that situation personally and didn't learn until after I was long gone from those people that I'd do exactly what Johnny was doing there. I remember when I was asked a question my heart would race with anxiety as I wondered, what if I say something that upsets them? What can I say afterwards to placate them? I was always thinking of my next word with such intensity that I'd shake, terrified to misstep. I also have family in the same situation with bad life partners. The best example would be my grandfather who found himself a woman my age (early 20's). At first everything seemed as normal as it could, but as the weeks and months would pass I noticed he no longer held his head up and made direct eye contact when he'd speak. He'd duck his chin if she was in the room and look to the floor as he'd reply to anyone and if she made even the slightest gesture he'd back up his statement and remove himself from the conversation immediately. He wouldn't even meet my gaze when we'd speak which I regret at the time I felt as him attempting to be dishonest with me. Though now after therapy and some years I've learned that this behavior is common in people in toxic relationships with a dominant partner who polices every little thing and reacts with violence or mental abuse to curb unwanted behavior. These toxic people know very well how to train someone with the right personality like a dog. They can get whatever reaction they want just by moving or vocalizing a certain way. Even a grunt or a loud nose exhale is enough to trigger that submissive behavior. Even now I struggle with what I perceive as aggressive body language, eye contact, and vocalizations even if the person I'm reacting to has no intentions or doesn't even know me that well.

It's not that simple. I never get the "their an actor" arguement as an actor 😂 like you have weeks sometimes MONTHS to prepare for a role. And even then you're acting/living the role but there's an element of you within it. Plus you usually rehearse for hours on end with a director guiding and correcting you. I doubt she bothered to do any of that for this interview, and even if she did, it would never be to the same extent as it would be for a show, movie, or play.

To be fair, acting for the screen to portray a fictional character is a very, very different proposition to making a lie credible in real life. Acting generally runs off an internally-consistent prepared script that runs to a known conclusion, and doesn't deviate much from it, and everything in the film supports the fiction.

Lying in real life involves improvised responses to questions that are not scripted, and the other players in the scene are doing all they can to derail any notional script you may have in your head and root out all the inconsistencies with identifiable facts. And there's no screenwriter, script editor, or director to make the scene support the fiction; facts are facts. People who think they can act their way through this are living in a fool's paradise even if they've got several Oscars on the shelf -- and Amber's nowhere near that calibre.

Acting skills are a very poor preparation for this -- especially if you're trying to apply them where they aren't going to work.

@Marija Kula "people like her don't come from happy and good families". That is very much not true & is misinformation that you probably shouldn't be spreading. I have zero idea what Amber's parents were like when she was a kid & I doubt very much that you have a lot more info than I do. 

Mental illness doesn't care if you have wonderful parents or sh!t parents. I had an idyllic childhood & was never ever hit, not even once. I wasn't emotionally or verbally abused & I wasn't neglected at all. I was sheltered from violence & negativity on all media until I finally was allowed to watch violent movies at age 17. I was supported in every single thing I did. They were about as perfect as everyone expects parents to be now but they did it in the 80s & 90s.

I was stalked & almost murdered my first few months at college & there are some issues I deal with that result from that but that has zero to do with my parents. My little brother had depression through his teen years & they did everything they could do. It wasn't from anything they did & is assumed by my brother's team of doctors to have a genetic component passed from my mother's father's family.

When he was in his early 20s a relationship ended & he locked himself in an enclosed trailer with a running snowmobile. My father drove the 22 minutes from their house to his in 12 & a half minutes. My dad was the one that ripped the locked door off of the enclosed trailer with his bare hands after he searched the property trying to find his son. He pulled his unconscious son from the enclosed racing trailer, called an ambulance & started CPR (thankfully my RN late husband had taught both my parents). My baby brother is only alive today because my Dad was paying attention & got him help. My dad went from having the same black hair that I have to almost completely gray overnight. It was that close. My brother didn't tip him off that he was ending his life but the text my brother did send my dad felt off to him so he leapt out of his tractor, jumped in his truck & floored it to my brother's house. 

My parents are terrific parents & 2 out of their 3 kids have mental illnesses. Negative parenting can absolutely produce mental illness in the kids raised in those homes but that isn't always the case & sometimes it just happens due to outside things or due to a genetic component. We have to stop accusing people of stuff without the necessary evidence. That's how we got here in the first place. Amber is the abuser & Johnny was the one being vilified until more evidence came out. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

I know several people who have been victims AND several people who have been falsely accused or labeled by various means.

There are different ways it happened. One guy just happened to have the same name (Let's say "Steve") as another person. His niece said that "Steve did stuff to her", essentially, but the thing was she had TWO uncles both named Steve and it was the OTHER uncle who was being accused. He happened to be her uncle and happened to have the same name, so when word started getting around people thought they meant him.

If you recall the whole scandal with priests, I had a priest friend who was watching the news one night. And guess what pops up? They started talking about the pedophile scandal and they put HIS PICTURE up on the screen.
Thing was they put the right name of the accused up, but they put the wrong picture up. I guess a picture of "some priest" was good enough. When he called to complain they basically made a correction in fine print that probably no one would even notice. Can you even imagine watching TV, you're not even accused of doing anything, but they post your picture anyway and say, "This guy is a pedophile"? It's horrific what the media can get away with and they don't even have to go out of their way to issue corrections - they can write some footnote somewhere and pretend that fixes the problem.

Then we knew another person and we actually believed her story about being raped, because that's what you do when someone tells you something like that. But we later found out there were massive holes in her story. For example, she claimed to be babysitting someone who wasn't born yet, as well as the fact that she had never babysat said person. When her story became filled with holes it became obvious that she had made up the lie that she'd been raped because she wanted to get sympathy from a guy she was dating way back when, and also wanted to explain why she wasn't a virgin (she was a very wild teenager) and explain her bad behavior. A rape story was something easy for her to use where people would say, "That explains a lot" and feel bad for her, but it turned out not a single fact lined up with her story. And the thing is that the dates things would have had to happen were very clear, so things that didn't add up couldn't have been a matter of 'just getting the dates a bit wrong'.

That's just three cases I know of where people have been falsely accused even accidentally, but a lot of people don't take it seriously. They want guilty until proven innocent. Of course I want my nieces to get justice if anything happens to them, but we want our nephews to get due process, too. No, this is normal. Here's why :
My mom is an elementary teacher. Long story short, a few students' parents where accusing some staff of things, my mom intervened to defend them and the staff used this as an opportunity to shift the blame to her, accusing her of being violent.

Now to the question "did you grab a child by the shoulder and and shook him while screaming ?"
She answered "yes". Just a plain old yes. It was a yes or no question after all.
But this yes do paint her as a violent person who shouldn't be near children. 

The truth to the story is that the child was endangering his classmates by playing with scissors and almost stabbed another kid in the eye even though my mom had told him to stop what he was doing.

Add a few more questions like this (well, less dramatic ones) where she admitted to actions she did but never gave context because it was yes or no questions. 
With her colleagues lying and omitting half the stories, the parents angry, the inexperienced director who called inspection before investigating if there was any truth in the claims.

And bam. You have an innocent forced to resign because the truth made them look super guilty.

In conclusion, never answer a yes or no question by yes or no when defending yourself.
It's usually better to give context. Because you never know what have been said in your back and if the person you are talking to is aware of the full story, or if they will even ask about the full story. @HeadCase0703 Making others comfortable is definitely a thing in this context, but while I've never been in this sort of position, I've had to talk at length to people about my experience with trauma, both from medical issues, and trauma brought on by others, such as robbery and car accidents.  When your brain is done analyzing things like that, it starts to protect itself from the bad effects of those memories.  Some people forget it altogether, some will refuse to talk so as not to put themselves in that mindset, others pick it apart for analysis as closure that nothing could be done about the situation.  I don't know of any studies so this information is by no means scientific, but of all the people I know that admitted to picking apart their trauma like I did, they chose to talk about the situation like a bad in-joke.  Some of us just laugh at our bad situations because the only other alternative for us is to just break down crying or screaming.  Those things just leave you exhausted.
